*****CSS Notes From Every Chapter****

**Basic CSS: Change the Color of Text**
  **The property responsible for an element's text is --> color: value;
  
**Basic CSS: Use a CSS Class to Style an Element
  **Syntax: <element class="special">Content</element>
  **A class can be accesed in CSS with .special {color:red; }
  **Classes allow you to use the same CSS styles on multiple HTML elements.
  
**Basic CSS: Change the Font Size of an Element
  **Font size is controlled by (font-size) property.
  **Syntax: p{font-size:16px; }
  
**Basic CSS: Set the Font Family of an Element
  **You can set which font an element should use, by using (font-family).
  **Syntax: p{font-family:monospaces or sans-serif or Verdana or Courier etc. }
  
**Basic CSS: Import a Google Font
  ** Google Fonts is a free library of web fonts that you can use in your CSS by referencing the font's URL.
  **https://fonts.google.com/
  **Impornt Font: <link href="https://fonts.googleapis.com/css?family=Lobster" rel="stylesheet" type="text/css">
  **Use it in CSS: p {font-family: "Lobster"; }
  
**Basic CSS: Specify How Fonts Should Degrade
  **When one font isn't available, you can tell the browser to "degrade" to another font.
  **p{font-family: 'Lobster', monospace,sans-serif; } 
  **If Lobster is not avasible, monospace will be used, if monospace is not avasible ,sans-serif will be used etc.
  
**Basic CSS: Size Your Images
  **CSS has a property called width that controls an element's width. smaller-image{ width:100px;}
  
**Basic CSS: Add Borders Around Your Elements
  **Color: border-color: red;
  **Width: border-width: 5px;
  **Style: border-style: solid;
  **Multiple classes to an element using its class attribute, by separating each class name with a space.
    For example:
  <img class="small-img green-border">
  .small-img{
   width:100px;
   }
 
a) .green-border{
  boder-width:10px;
  border-style: solid
  border-color:green;
}

**Basic CSS: Add Rounded Corners 
  **We can round out those corners with a CSS property called (border-radius).
  **Syntax: a) {boder-radius:10px; }
  
**Basic CSS: Make Circular Images with a border-radius
  **Specify the border-radius with  %
  **Syntax: a) {border-radius: 50%;}
  
**Basic CSS: Give a Background Color to a div Element
  **You can set an element's background color with the (background-color)
  **<div class="silver-background"> ...... </div>
    .silver-background{background-color: silver; }
    
**Basic CSS: Set the id of an Element
  **There are several benefits to using id attributes: You can use an id to style a single element and later 
  you'll learn that you can use them to select and modify specific elements with JavaScript.
  **ID's should be uniq
  **A id can be accesed in CSS with #uniq {color:red; }
  **Sytax: <element id="uniq">Content</element>
  
**Basic CSS: Adjust the Padding of an Element
  **Three important properties control the space that surrounds each HTML element: padding, margin, and border. 
  **padding - space between text and border
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
